        <content type="html" xml:base="http://localhost/tea-blog/pettiagalla-op-ceylon/">&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http:&#x2F;&#x2F;localhost&#x2F;tea-blog&#x2F;pettiagalla-op-ceylon&#x2F;image1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Pettiagalla Op Ceylon packet&quot; &#x2F;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http:&#x2F;&#x2F;localhost&#x2F;tea-blog&#x2F;pettiagalla-op-ceylon&#x2F;image2.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Tea close-up&quot; &#x2F;&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;http:&#x2F;&#x2F;localhost&#x2F;tea-blog&#x2F;pettiagalla-op-ceylon&#x2F;image3.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Tea brewed tea&quot; &#x2F;&gt;
This is some bloody good tea…
It tastes very fruity in a good way, although orange in the title is a reference to dutch royalty rather than the taste; however it seems to actually have a really subtle background taste of orange in it. Its similar to a typical darjeeling with its texture but has a bit more body. Some what of a medium weight tea and a new favorite for the moment.
“If god had dandruff it would be these tea leaves” - Darren Jennings (my flatmate)&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
